H.R. 4275, as amended, authorizes the Coast Guard for the next
five years at fiscally responsible levels to continue carrying out
these critical missions, with support to revitalize afloat and air as-
sets, improve the Coast Guard’s crumbling shoreside infrastructure
and facilities, and revitalize antiquated IT systems.
Investments in the Coast Guard
The Coast Guard has endured chronic undercapitalization for
decades—jeopardizing the ability for the Service to carry out its
missions. As a consequence, many Coast Guard assets were, and
still are, operated well beyond their planned service life because
funds to carry out the recapitalization were not forthcoming. While
significant progress has been made in recapitalizing some assets,
heavy icebreakers, medium endurance cutters and rotary wing air-
craft are aging out before they can be replaced. The advanced age
and lack of maintenance on these legacy assets limits the amount
of time they are available to carry out Coast Guard mission and
increases maintenance costs.
To address these capability gaps, Congress approved Pub. L.
119–21, which provides $24.59 billion in investments for the Serv-
ice’s surface, air and shoreside assets.6 H.R. 4275, as amended,
builds on these investments by authorizing substantial growth over
the next five years in the Coast Guard’s Procurement, Construc-
tion, and Investment Account to finish the modernization of the ro-
tary wing fleet, complete the Waterway Commerce Cutter program,
build a Great Lakes icebreaker, slow the growth in the backlog of
shoreside projects, continue the growth of unmanned systems to
provide better maritime domain awareness, and build other future
Coast Guard capabilities. At the same time, H.R. 4275, as amend-
ed, authorizes substantial growth in the Coast Guard’s Operations
and Support Account, bringing the Service’s total annual authoriza-
tion to more than $20 billion by 2028.
While the Committee supports funding growth based on dem-
onstrated need, the Committee has significant concerns about the
Coast Guard’s ability to effectively carry out its major acquisition
programs. The Committee notes that nearly all of the Coast Guard
surface acquisition programs have suffered from cost overruns and
delays, and in some cases, the Service will be receiving fewer hulls
than the number for which they signed contracts. The Committee
is pleased with recent progress on the Polar Security Cutter Pro-
gram but has substantial concerns with the progress of the first
phase of the Offshore Patrol Cutter Program. The Committee con-
tinues to strongly support the domestic maritime industrial base—
both in terms of the economic benefits it brings to our country and
the national security readiness that it provides in times of war or
national emergency. Accordingly, H.R. 4275, as amended, strength-
ens the requirements of section 1151 of title 14, U.S.C., by man-
dating additional notification requirements should the President
determine a national security exemption from the prohibition on
foreign construction of Coast Guard cutters is necessary.
