The Committee also recognizes the need for the Coast Guard to
update its aging fleet of air assets. While the Committee continues
to have concerns with the suitability of the MH–60 airframe for
certain Coast Guard missions, the Committee appreciates the need
to phase out MH–65 dolphin helicopters which are no longer being
produced and will suffer from a rapidly increasing scarcity of parts.
To support the Committee’s understanding of Coast Guard aircraft
needs, H.R. 4275, as amended, requires a detailed analysis of Coast
Guard rotary wing requirements. The Committee will continue to
closely monitor the transition as it moves forward.
Given the Coast Guard’s acquisition challenges, and dem-
onstrated need for significant oversight, H.R. 4275, as amended,
prohibits the Coast Guard from spending the funding appropriated
by Pub. L. 119–21 until certain statutorily required reports on how
those funds will be expended are delivered to Congress and man-
dates regular reporting on the disbursement and use of those
funds. Similarly, the measure restricts funding for fixed wing and
rotary wing assets until the Service provides a report detailing the
sufficiency of the Coast Guards aviation assets to meet mission de-
mands, which was due to the Committee 18 months ago.7 Impor-
tantly, H.R. 4275, as amended, also updates Coast Guard acquisi-
tion processes to provide the best value for the taxpayer and per-
mits the Service to use vessel construction managers to support
major acquisition programs. This includes the ability for the service
to choose the best contractor for the job, not simply the cheapest,
which has historically led to poor performance by the contractor
and increased costs to remedy the project delays and cost overruns.
As part of the push to grow the service by over 15,000 personnel,
the Committee recognizes the need to fund and improve other as-
pects of the service that would provide critical support services
such as medical care, medical facilities, childcare resources, and
housing. H.R. 4275, as amended, requires the Coast Guard to pro-
vide a report to Congress on how it intends to support the service’s
growth if the budget submission does not reflect a commensurate
increase in its Operations and Support funding account. The Com-
mittee views this requirement as a critical oversight tool in order
to prevent furthering the backlog of funding for personnel and in-
frastructure.
With the increase in funding across the board, the Committee
also recognizes the need for investments in the workforce. The
Coast Guard is understaffed in both medical care providers and
specialists and childcare providers. An investment in the hiring
and career retention of these individuals is critical for providing
the necessary levels of care for servicemembers, especially in light
of the anticipated growth of the force.
Secretary of the Coast Guard
The Coast Guard is the only armed service without a Service
Secretary. The Committee is concerned that the Service’s lack of
representation within the Department, the Administration and
among the other service Secretaries has harmed its ability to effec-
tively advocate for its needs. As a result, the Service has suffered
from decades of underinvestment, which had led to a decline in
