Report on Craft Preventative Maintenance and Monitoring
The Committee recognizes the importance of sustaining the
United States Coast Guard’s small boat and cutter fleets and safe-
guarding the health of their crews, who operate in some of the
most challenging maritime environments in the world. The Com-
mittee is aware of proven, commercially available technologies ca-
pable of securely collecting and capturing vessel and operator data
in offline, austere conditions. These technologies have dem-
onstrated value in enhancing safety, extending operational life, and
improving mission readiness by identifying maintenance and
health issues before they become critical.
Accordingly, the Committee encourages the Coast Guard to
evaluate opportunities to integrate preventative maintenance capa-
bilities and monitoring systems across its surface fleet, particularly
for high-use, high-tempo platforms such as fast response cutters
and deployable boats. The Committee believes these technologies
offer a cost-effective means of improving material readiness, reduc-
ing risk to personnel, and extending the service life of critical as-
sets.
Therefore, the Committee directs the Coast Guard to submit a
briefing to the House Transportation and Infrastructure Committee
not later than December 1, 2025, on its efforts to explore such tech-
nologies, any barriers to their adoption, and resource requirements
necessary to pilot or field these systems at scale.
Maritime Transportation
The maritime transportation system (MTS) is a key contributor
to commerce and is essential to the economic health and prosperity
of the United States. The past few years have demonstrated the
fragility of not only the United States supply chain, but the supply
chain worldwide. Recently, the maritime supply chain has faced ad-
ditional threats from violent Houthi attacks targeting numerous ci-
vilian and military vessels. This has caused several of the largest
shipping companies to halt or limit transits through the Red Sea
and Suez Canal, which traditionally facilitated the flow of 20 per-
cent of container shipping.8 Modernizing the operations of the MTS
is more important than ever in the wake of a myriad of threats to
the supply chain. The Committee is committed to supporting the
MTS and growing our shipbuilding industry.
H.R. 4275, as amended, contains provisions to boost the pool of
qualified United States mariners by reducing bureaucratic delays
and barriers to Americans seeking a seagoing career. It seeks to
make permanent reductions to the lengths of certain periods of
service initiated in the National Defense Authorization Act for Fis-
cal Year 2024.9 Additionally, the legislation amends the require-
ments for certain merchant mariner credentials to consider ad-
vances in technology and training, aligns Coast Guard require-
