Implementation of Accountability and Transparency Review Rec-
ommendations
H.R. 4275, as amended, strengthens protections for members of
the Coast Guard from sexual assault and harassment and in-
creases transparency within the Service. Operation Fouled Anchor
was a Coast Guard investigation initiated in 2014 that revealed in-
cidents of rape, assault, and other misconduct at the Coast Guard
Academy (Academy) occurring from 1990 until 2006.10 The report
uncovered a repeated pattern of mishandling cases and not holding
perpetrators accountable—in part driven by efforts to protect the
reputation of the Academy.11 Furthermore, the Committee’s inves-
tigation revealed broken processes that failed to properly track de-
cision making with regards to prosecutorial decisions. Despite the
Committee’s demonstrated interest in curbing sexual assault and
sexual harassment, the Coast Guard chose to withhold the report
from Congress. Even worse, the decision to bury the report resulted
in a failure to implement the recommendations from Operation
Fouled Anchor. After the report became public, the Service under-
took an Accountability and Transparency Review (ATR), which in-
cluded recommendations to prevent and better respond to future
sexual assault and sexual harassment incidents.12 On November
27, 2023, the Coast Guard released the ATR, along with the Com-
mandant’s Directed Actions, which seek to mitigate instances of
harassment, assault, and other mistreatment.13
H.R. 4275, as amended, provides additional authorities to the
Coast Guard to protect its service members, aligns Coast Guard
practices with the practices of other military services, and man-
dates additional transparency and accountability as the actions are
implemented.
Other Matters
H.R. 4275, as amended, seeks to improve personnel conditions to
promote retention and attract the best qualified applicants. Among
other things, it updates provides direct hire authority for civilian
faculty at the Coast Guard Academy and authorizes maternity uni-
form allowances for officers.
As autonomous systems become more common in the maritime
domain, H.R. 4275 seeks to advance the Coast Guard’s capabilities
with regards to the use of such technologies. The legislation estab-
lishes a National Autonomous Maritime Systems Advisory Com-
mittee within the Coast Guard, comprised of various stakeholders
